# Transformer architectures

There are 3 main transformer architectural variants:
**Encoder, Decoder, and Sequence-to-Sequence**
We will go into all 3 of them and explore how we can use them for NLP tasks

---
## Encoder
- Use only the encoder side of the transformer
- attention layers have access to all the words in the inital sentence
- "Bi-directional" attention (aka auto-encoding models)
- Pretraining:
    - Corrupting the sentence
    - masking random words
    - tasking the model to find or rebuild the sentence

- Best suited for:
    - Sentence classification
    - NER
    - question answering
---
## Decoder
- Only decoder side of the transformer
- Attention layers only have access to the words positioned before the word in the sentence
- Auto-regressive
- Pretrianing: 
    - Predicting the next word in the sentence
- Best suited for text gen

### Modern LLMs
- Large parameters
- Pretraining: Learns to predict the next token
- Instruction fine tuning: model is fine-tuned to follow instructions


## Encoder-decoder models

- Both parts of transformer arcitecture
- Attention layers in encoder can access all words in the inital sentence
- Attention layers in decoder can access only the words right before the given word
- Pretraining:
    - Reconstructing a sentence for the input is corrupted
    - T5 model is pretrained by replacing random text with mask token and the task is to predict the text the mask token replaces
- Best suited for:
    - summarization
    - Translation
    - Generative question-answering

